article.description: Ruthie Bolton scored five of her 12 points in the second overtime, giving the Sacramento Monarchs a 78-77 victory Thursday night over the New York Liberty.
article.headline: Monarchs outlast Liberty in two OTs
article.linkText: Monarchs outlast Liberty in two OTs for first win
article.story:
SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- Although no longer an All-Star,
veteran Ruthie Bolton can still play like one at times.

She helped rescue the Sacramento Monarchs on Thursday night, scoring five of her 12 points in the second overtime, giving the Monarchs a 78-77 victory over the New York Liberty.

"I knew it was about my time, I needed to come through,'' said
Bolton, who recently turned 35. "I feel like I'm still a money
player.''
	 
  Bolton converted a left-handed layup, giving Sacramento (1-4)
the lead for good at 75-74. She then hit a pull-up baseline jumper
with 1:12 remaining for a three-point lead.

"Those two shots Ruthie made were both tough ones,'' New York
coach Richie Adubato said. "And they just broke our back.''

Bolton wasn't through. She stripped the ball from Crystal
Robinson at the defensive end. Fouled on the play, she converted
one of two free throws, putting the Monarchs ahead 78-74 with 2.5
seconds left.

Becky Hammon made a 3-pointer at the buzzer for the Liberty
(6-3).

"We needed this victory to get the monkey off our backs and
move on,'' Sacramento coach Maura McHugh said. "This is a big
victory, New York is a great team. We certainly didn't make it easy
on ourselves.''

It was a solid overall game for Monarchs point guard Ticha
Penicheiro, who had 23 points, nine assists, five rebounds, five
steals and converted 12 of 14 free throws. La'Keshia Frett added 14
points for the Monarchs and Kedra Holland-Corn had 13.

Tamika Whitmore led the Liberty with 21 points and Tari Phillips
had 20. Both Robinson and Hammon had 13 points.

Robinson nearly won the game in the first overtime, coming off a
screen for a long perimeter shot that nearly went in at the buzzer.

Trailing 62-60, Robinson took an inbounds pass in the lane and
dribbled in for the layup with 10.8 seconds left. Penicheiro missed
a runner in the lane with four seconds left, sending the game into
overtime.

"This was our fourth road game in six nights, I don't know
where we found the energy to play two overtimes,'' Adubato said.
"I think they thought we were out of it late in regulation, but we
made some big shots to get it to overtime.''

With the score tied at 58, Penicheiro was fouled on a drive by
Teresa Weatherspoon. She made the shot and converted the free throw
as the Monarchs took a three-point lead with 34 seconds remaining.

Monarchs' All-Star center Yolanda Griffith missed the game and
will be out the next four weeks with a bulging disk in her neck.
